{"questionId":"22639232","questionHtml":"<p>By considering the discriminant, or otherwise, show that the probability of the graph of such a randomly generated quadratic function having only one <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-intercept is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>Note:</strong> In parts (c) – (f), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>, for example, represents an ordered <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>-tuple <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>recognizes that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> (or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>attempts to use <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>determines one value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> only (seen anywhere) OR one value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math> only (seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>attempts to find a possible value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>determines one value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> only (seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>recognizes that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> must be a multiple of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> must be a multiple of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>determines one value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> only (seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>attempts to find a possible value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>determines one value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></math> from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math> only (seen anywhere)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;possible way OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;possible ways OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>:</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;OR <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> possible way OR&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>therefore the required probability is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>5</mn><mn>216</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[6 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22639232","referenceCode":"24M.3.AHL.TZ2.2c","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"By considering the discriminant, or otherwise, show that the probability of the graph of such a randomly generated quadratic function having only one x-intercept is 5216.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 6]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","Topic 4—Statistics and probability","SL 4.5—Probability concepts, expected numbers","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.7—Solutions of quadratic equations and inequalities, discriminant and nature of roots"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}